  • [r6488] CMakeModules/EmergentDefaults.cmake, configure, include/vectormath.h[ADD], src/emergent/leabra/LeabraConSpec.cpp, src/emergent/leabra/LeabraConSpec.h, src/emergent/leabra/LeabraConSpec_inlines.h, src/emergent/leabra/LeabraUnitSpec.cpp, src/emergent/leabra/LeabraUnitSpec.h, src/emergent/lib/CMakeLists.txt, src/temt/ta/vectormath.h[ADD] * ./configure option --not-native -- otherwise it assumes -march=native -- use for packaging
    * all relevant optimizations in std RelWithDebInfo config -- I was getting weird errors for Release on loading several projects -- overoptimization bugs somewhere..
    * clang compiler enables USE_SSE8 by default
    * sse8 version of send netin delta, compute_dwt -- compute weights was too slow
    * added LeabraUnitSpec::opt_thresh.xcal_lrn -- if sending activity is below this threshold, no learning is needed in xcal -- big time saver
    * lowered res on wt_sig_fun to 1.0e-4 instead of 1.0e-5 which seemed excessive and was
    only necessary when doing too many conversions
    * overall performance is now 20-40% faster than when optimization process started!

  • [r6394] src/temt/ta/iMainWindowViewer.cpp, src/temt/ta/iMainWindowViewer.h, src/temt/ta/taBase.cpp, src/temt/ta/taBase.h, src/temt/ta/taFiler.cpp, src/temt/ta/taFiler.h, src/temt/ta/taProject.cpp, src/temt/ta/taProject.h Added a user settable flag "save_as_only" on project that disables "save" action but keeps "save as" action available. When "save as" is executed the file name has "_copy" appended to the file name, for example, LeabraStd.proj becomes LeabraStd_copy.proj. This should keep users from accidently overwriting files that are demos or tutorials not meant to be overwritten. This isn't truely "read-only" because the user can change the name in the save dialog but then the flag on the project is user settable anyway. The "save_as_only" flag is set to false on the copy so the copy can be "saved".

  • [r5668] src/temt/ta/ta_imgproc.cpp, src/temt/ta/ta_imgproc.h DOH! woke up this morning realizing that the whole problem with tiling is using edge_mode
    = WRAP in the SampleImageWindow -- somehow that was a legacy setting and so changing it
    to BORDER fixes all the weird tiling issues!! and the key difference is that the Sample
    method produces MUCH smoother results -- was getting really blocky bad aliasing effects
    in the objrec model -- now looks so much better and performance is better too.
    sorry for all the churn (at least we now have good alpha support and some handy new
    functions!)

    ** a = [1,2,3; 4,5,6]; = matrix with 2 rows x 3 columns
    ** a = [1:5:1]; = 2d matrix with inner dim = 3, used for slicing operations
    ** a = [:]; = above with 0:-1:1 defaults
    ** a = [::-1] = reverse order, etc etc
    * python-style slicing and indexing for List, String, and soon Matrix, Array objects
    ** new Variant taBase::Elem(Variant idx) function that parses idx as a matrix and
    does the right thing in different taBase subclasses (only List impl now)
    ** in case where Elem returns multiple items, a new List object (clone token) is made,
    filled with Link pointers to original objects, and a "el_view" matrix is installed
    with active indices or a byte mask -- iterator and display routines use this view
    to only expose selected items from original list -- same semantics as python.
    ** added new generic TA iterator that uses view filtering -- may require further tweaking
    for Matrix class
    ** had to add cssTA_Base ref of ptr when ptr_cnt = 0 and we don't own -- this happens
    and wasn't supported before -- oversight. hopefully doesn't cause new issues.. :)
    ** new cssTA_Matrix obj to support matrix-specific operators etc
    ** coming: datatable and taGroup will support multidimensional indexing semantics -- first
    level is cols for datatable, subgroups for taGroup, next levels are items within, etc.
    ** fixed css auto-type to unspecified objects -- a = 1; a = "foo"; a = matrix per above all
    give var appropriate type automatically -- had extra 'term' in yacc syntax -- weird.
    ** matrix index model will automatically support matlab-style "find" etc..
    ** css will auto-detect matrix args to functions that take an element, and unroll using
    iterator across all elements -- not in place yet -- will work with user-defined funs too

  • [r4915] plugins/LIBLINEAR/LIBLINEAR.cpp, plugins/LIBLINEAR/LIBLINEAR.h, plugins/LIBLINEAR/LIBLINEAR.proj.gz, plugins/LIBLINEAR/liblinear-1.8/Makefile, plugins/LIBLINEAR/liblinear-1.8/linear.cpp * Major refactoring. New paradigm allows all available system memory to be used:
    1) Stream data to file in LIBSVM format
    2) Save the DataTable to file
    3) Reset the DataTable
    3) Read the LIBSVM format data from file into a problem
    4) Train/Predict/CrossValidate etc.
    5) Destroy LIBSVM data
    6) Read back in the DataTable.

    If above process has already been done in the past including ".libsvm"
    in the fname will skip to loading the LIBSVM format data.

    * Implemented precision, recall, fmeasure statistics based on probability mass

    * only projects are saved with name paths -- everything else is same as before with
    numeric indicies. thus, only projects are svn mergable. this is necessary to enable

    of existing objects.

    overwritten during project loading!
    * user is prevented from loading a project file over top of existing project object.

    then we should be good to go.. GetValStr and SetValStr routines are key points of entry
    for fixing these issues.
    * also, changing the name of an object automatically ensures that names are unique within
    list scope.
    * never redefine GetName() for an object that actually has a name field, to return
    something other than the actual name!

  • [r2799] src/emergent/leabra/leabra.cpp, src/emergent/leabra/leabra.h major optimization of spike mode in leabra: before it used exponential decay of
    activation to simulate synaptic currents, requiring redundant sends of activations
    (very expensive), now it just sends the activation once when it spikes and then
    stores results in a moving time window buffer from which synaptic current is computed.
    also now has a full alpha function for synatic current, including separate rise and
    decay time constants. system is now fully integrate-and-fire compliant and
    we should get major speedup from using spikes.. if it will work with learning..

    being dragged down by tail of distribution, and only being concerned with the
    units right around the "edge". this also generalizes well to the k=1 case,
    where it is equivalent to std (non avg based) KWTA, which is where it is
    typically used.

  • [r1734] 1733 has the "alpha"-level implementation of the new copy paradigm

    For now, this enables, in principle, any kind of object to be copied
    to any other kind of object. It is now possible to copy a different
    Matrix type, ex. int to float. We will expand this a bit to
    allow copying of DataCol and Tables where you leave your cols
    in place, and just copy the data. We will probably also find
    use for this in specs, networks, and such.

    A number of "core" changes have been made, which may break things.

    Names:

    * we no longer copy the object name by default -- this may break
    some things, ex it broke DataCol, so I had to add that in
    (for now)

    Lists:

    * duplicate now puts the el after the one you choose, and gives
    it the default name

  • [r1725] Since last checkin:

    DND/CLIP

    * dnd/clip standard ops fixed/tested
    * added all the ops to the main and context menus
    * group operations now working, both inproc and ext
    * added new Assign op -- paste/drop an obj to assign
    it to another one -- you can assign from any
    class >= the class being assigned
    * note: Duplicate is in limbo, pending implementation
    (flags/menus are there, just needs impl) -- issue
    is that Dupe is a weird hybrid of a SRC and DST op
    and our paradigm doesn't well support it, but it
    is probably hackable (like Delete, but Delete is
    way easier, because there is no real operation to
    do, vs. Dupe, which requires making then inserting
    new objects)

    Issues:

    * something not right when using main menu to paste stuff
    into a list -- ticket 387

    USER INFORMING

    * all user messages now go through standard system
    message dialogs
    * taMisc:: apis are unchanged (should normally use
    those)
    * taiChoiceDialog is now a subclass of QMessageBox
    * there is now a taMisc::Confirm -- this should be
    used for all popup messages that just require Ok
    * i replace all the Choice(blah, Ok) calls with
    this -- it is not a big deal, but is more standard
    since the icon is a simple message, not a question
    * error dialogs now have a Copy To Clipboard

    I have hoped to keep the Choice guys working the same,
    but there could be some differences, particularly,
    the system will now sometimes reorder the buttons
    in the dialog, but note that the *chs* values will
    always be correct (the order you supplied them)

    WARNING: there is a chance the order of buttons on
    your favorite confirmation dialog could have changed,
    depending on your platform -- when you use this new
    release, pay small attention to choice dialogs
    when they first come up, before hitting the button
    in the place you are used to!! (sorry, there was
    nothing i could do about this, it is baked into
    Qt)

    I eliminated most of the few remaining manual
    calls to taiChoiceDialog,
    and replaced with calls to taMisc::Choice -- it is
    not forbidden to use the dialog directly, but please
    note that I've changed the api so that the msg and
    the button list are separate -- but apart from that
    it is similar to before.

    You can use the dialogs directly, particularly if
    you want to supply a wintitle -- note the order of
    the args has changed slightly -- the title is now
    after the msg, since the title is optional -- it
    defaults to the app name (per MS guidelines)

    PROGRAMS

    * very major change to how Method args are handled:
    the default value is NO LONGER set into the arg
    itself, it is only DISPLAYED for the user reference --
    the reason is that the combination of maketa
    parsing along with css just does not properly handle
    default arguments -- so instead, they are tracked
    but left blank -- if you want all the def args to
    use their defaults, do nothing -- the call will simply
    not pass those args, and the defaults will get used
    -- if you *want* to use some defaults, THEN a non-default
    after those defaults, then you will have to manually
    copy in the default values to the ones before your
    non-default ex:

    MyMeth(int a, int b=1, int c=2, int d=3)

    if you want the defaults, do nothing, and just set a;
    but say you wanted d to be 4, you'd have to do this:
    a=val, b=1, c=2, d=4

    The handling of expr value itself has not changed at all,
    and any values that are in saved programs will load as
    before, so anything that is currently working, will work
    identically -- you don't need to do anything -- this only
    applies to when you add a new MethodCall or StaticMethodCall

    * method args are now checked to insure required values
    are supplied

    * note that there is an issue with how our system parses
    default arguments from the source code, such that
    there can be ambiguities, particularly with string
    arguments, since we don't keep the quotation signs --
    so this will be an outstanding issue -- you just have
    to use some commonsense try to figure out what makes
    sense, ex. _nilString means the nilstring value,
    not the literal string "_nilString"; for const char*
    args, 0 will typically mean NULL, not "0", etc.

    * note that there is no way to resupply C++ default
    arguments, such as default reference variables -- but
    these cases are fairly rare, and we will try to fix up
    the api to help avoid exposing these types of tricky
    methods to the user

    note: i did test our standard projects, and they all
    seem to load and run fine

    Tickets:

    336 - APPLY_IMMED now works for specs
    324 - closed
    373 - CONDSHOW leaves blanks in normal edit
    320 - changing var/arg values only
    334 -- copy/paste/drop to self is bad
    134 - dnd/clip changes
    367 - dnd not preserving item order
    214 - defchild issues
    363 - spec on spec crash
    357 - added Copy To Clipboard to error boxes
    385 - meth args must stale prog
    364 - defargs issue, no longer a direct issue, so i
    just bumped this way down in priority

  • [r795] find ./ -name Makefile.am -type f -print | xargs sed -i \.bck -r 's/(lib[a-zA-Z]*)(\@PDP_SUFFIX\@)(_la)/\1\2\_@PDP_VERSION\@\3/g'

    =)

    this actually takes less time than opening every file and doing a find/replace

    notes:
    * css++ is now css
    * libta is now libtacss
    i think the craziest construct supported is:
    libtacss_debug_nogui_mpi-3.5.so.0.0.0
  • 2006-08-21 01:00 mingus
  • [r794] * overall package versioning is major.minor, and now at 3.5. e.g., pdp++-3.5.tar.gz
    * library versioning follows libtool standards, e.g., current.revision.age. these are both well documented at the top of configure.ac, which is the place to modify them just before a release. starting at libta/pdp.so.0.0.0
    * Now checking for existence of pdp++/css++ in the directory to be installed into to avoid conflict with <=3.2 versions (we will never conflit with libs). Suggest user use a configure option to rename, e.g.,

    pdp++ configuration warnings:
    * pdp++ is already installed in /home/mingus/bin. Consider renaming with --program-suffix=SUFFIX

    * Automatically suffixing based on build mode (e.g., pdp_debug_nogui_mpi) now only occurs in debug mode.
    * libraries no longer have a hard-coded "4" suffix
    * cleaned up svn:ignore properties to get rid of bogus `svn status' listings such as:

    ? src/css_bin/.deps

    I documented this on the dev wiki. Note: this will cause you to see every folder in the source modified the next time you update (I think). This is *just* the properties being updated on those folders recursively. http://grey.colorado.edu/cgi-bin/trac.cgi/wiki/SettingSvnProperties

  • [r316] = Changes =
    * Moved our build modes to PDP_SET_BUILD_MODES in acsite.m4
    * SIM_AC_COMPILER_OPTIMIZATION allows arbitrary optimization override
    * Fixed optimization in libcss
    * Nuked ACX_PTHREAD in favor of SIM...
    * Moved a lot of configure checks into debug mode only. These particular checks only set defines we don't use, and thus are only useful when the system doesn't build for some reason
    * More reverse engineering of gendsp.sh.in

    = Bugs =
    * Some libraries are passed twice. This doesn't hurt anything; it's just confusing.

  • [r308] Primary changes:
    * In GUI mode we link against QtCore, QtGui, Qt3Support, QtOpenGL, QtNetwork, Coin, SoQt and define QT3_SUPPORT
    * In GUI + Debug mode we add QtTest
    * Now using SIM_AC_HAVE_SOQT_IFELSE and SIM_AC_HAVE_COIN_IFELSE
    * Initial support for generating a digital studio project file via SIM_AC_MSVC_DSP_ENABLE_OPTION

    Others:

    * Mangling renamed to Infixing
    * Nuked MDL_HAVE_OPENGL and AX_HAVE_GL in favor of SIM_AC_HAVE_OPENGL_IFELSE
    * Nuked CHECK_ZLIB in favor of SIM_AC_HAVE_ZLIB_IFELSE
    * Nuked BNV_HAVE_QT
    * Added SIM_AC_HAVE_LIBJPEG_IFELSE
    * Initial support for generating pkg-config .pc files

    TODO:
    * Modify SIM_AC_HAVE_QT_IFELSE to work in our project under our different modes (right now this is happening outside the macro)
    * But keep it easy to merge in changes that Coin might make to the macro
    * This includes a sed statement to modify the Qt libraries to be Qt_debug
    * Here are the modes:
    --gui
    QtCore, QtGui, Qt3Support, QtOpenGL, QtNetwork
    Coin, SoQt
    -DQT3_SUPPORT

    --gui-debug (same as gui)
    add:QtTest

    --no gui
    QtCore, QtNetwork

    --no gui-debug (same as no-gui)
    add:QtTest
    * make make force_ta work unconditionally in individual projects
    * Before release make sure to nuke extraneous autoconf macros
    * Nuke ACX_PTHREAD completely in favor of SIM_AC_HAVE_PTHREAD_IFELSE
    * Coin has some Debugging and Optimization macros that may be preferable to our own



    Bugs:
    * My initial attempt at no-gui QtCore is still present and broken

    * Something wrong with pthread and recent GCC update via yum

  • [r246] subversion supports arbitrary properties on files. this adds the built in magic property of svn:ignore to the following globs: 'Makefile Makefile\.in configure \.deps config.log config.status *stamp* config\.h\.in autom4te\.cache libtool aclocal\.m4'. this means they won't show up with svn status etc... let me know ASAP if this causes any problems for you. they can be deleted with svn propdelf

  • [r237] *Added configuration message at the very end. I borrowed it from the Free Edition of Coin which is GPL'ed. To add more use SIM_AC_CONFIGURATION_SETTING and SIM_AC_CONFIGURATION_WARNING. Currently looks like the following, and I added many more warnings which aren't shown here since there are no problems with the build. If you guys want other things just send me a note:

    PDP++ configuration settings:
    GUI: Disabled
    MPI: Enabled
    Debuging: Enabled
    Optimization: -g -O0
    Mangling: Enabled. Prototype of bins\libs is pdp_nogui_debug_mpi++\libpdp_nogui_debug_mpi.a

    *Maketa is still independent but no longer has its own configure script. This was necessary in order to support the configuration message, as the maketa configure always ran after it was printed. Cached configure now runs in ~7 seconds!

    *Added `make ifnames' to top-level configure for printing all the package defines

  • 2005-09-18 20:18 mingus
  • [r15] Updated to include all *TA* files within EXTRA_DIST. This is necessary because we will be distributing premade versions of these files. Since we have also told the autotools that we explicitly make these files if they are not present, we need to tell the autotools to also distribute them initially. This update also creates a .PHONY target for all the files in /src/ta/ios-g++-3.1/. This is because these files are never made. In order to pass 'make distcheck' there must be a rule to bring them up to date, but since that never happens we'll use a phony one.
